message.content:
A Larus marinus is a large seabird commonly known as the northern gannet. 

It has a striking appearance with a white body, black-tipped wings, and a yellowish head. 

The bill of the bird is long and pointy, and is used to catch fish. 

The texture of its feathers is sleek and streamlined, helping it to be an efficient swimmer and diver. 

Larus marinus can be found nesting on coastal cliffs, offshore islands, and rocky outcrops. 

The bird is often seen flying low over the water, scanning for fish to catch. 

Northern gannets are known for their bold diving prowess, plunging into the water from heights of up to 30m to catch their prey.
